                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18261207-249-defend1382 t18261207-249-deflabel1450"></join>; Mr. Hebborn's truck stood down the gateway - I was standing there on the 1st of April; the prisoner came and said he came for McCree's truck; Hebborn is a <rs id="t18261207-249-viclabel1451" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18261207-249-victim1383 t18261207-249-viclabel1451"></join>, and had lived with McCree; I asked if he was sure McCree had sent him for it; he said he did, as he had a quantity of baggage to bring down; he took it, and went towards the Custom-house with it - I saw no more of him.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM HEBBORN. I am a porter. This is my truck. I never sent the prisoner for it, or authorised him to get possession of it. I have not seen it since. I took him on the 17th of November. He said he had taken it away, but never said what had become of it. I could not find him before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. A man came and asked if I wanted a job; he took me up the wharf, and I assisted him with the truck. - Another man joined us, and they took me to Bow, and at last both went away; - they returned, and began swearing, and saying it was not worth the trouble; they could get but 12s. for it.</p>
